You have to define implementation of `x` in the class. Interface definition only defines &quot;shape&quot; of an object. 

TypeScript cannot know how you want to implement the `x`. For example, instead of using field, you could have valid implementation of `A` interface using getter, setter and backing field:

```typescript
class B implements A {
    private _x: number | null = null;

    get x(): number | null {
        return this._x;
    };

    set x(value: number | null) {
        this._x = value;
    }

    setX(val: number) {
        this.x = val;
    }
}
```

Typescript playground [link][1].


  [1]: http://www.typescriptlang.org/play/#code/JYOwLgpgTgZghgYwgAgILIN4Chm+QDwC5kQBXAWwCNpkAfE0gG0YG4c8BnCMADQAoAbnEbEyVaAEpiAgPbAAJmwC+WLAkZwOHZACFkwcgAdGEchHDb02PMkNRgQyMgD6RBuKh0GzZAF5vrKo2AObcBHxS7tSe9GQ+1jZ4UNykUCDIYAAWwBwAdK5sNkps7LhcYOFCjKQQohTRXnGMEpiliVk5+fh+yFU1hXgqbeX8VXUeLQmJGdl53f5VA7gqSkA

When your class is implementing interface then it **doesn&#39;t mean that properties from an interface have been already declared in a class**. All that interface is doing here for you it&#39;s just checking your types in class:

Ok:

    class B implements A {
        x: number | null = null;
        ...
    }


Not ok:

    class B implements A {
        x: number | string= &quot;&quot;;
        ...
    }

But you can&#39;t use &#39;x&#39; without declaring it in class and you have declared it in class as null which matches the type number | null. An interface is **only to check types used in class**, not further implementation.

